An application does not sufficiently validate user input that allows an attacker to create a malformed log file or inject an arbitrary code.

A web application can generate log file entities based on user input data. Because of insufficient data processing, an attacker can inject dividing characters and therefore create a malformed log file entity, making it impossible to automatically process this file. Also, an attacker can inject malware and use it for further attacks.

Please fins the vulnerable script example below:

                
$result = $authService->authenticate($login, $password);

if (!$result->isValid()) {
    $log->write("Authentication failed for user '$login'");
}

Recommendations

We recommend you process log file data to delete or escape formaztting characters.

Links

  • Log Forging https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Log_Forging
  • CWE-117: Improper Output Neutralization for Logs http://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/117.html

A web application can generate executable code base on user input. An attacker can execute arbitrary code if there is no processing of special characters that can modify syntax or code behavior.

A vulnerable script example:

                
if (isset($_GET['documents'])) {
    $documents = eval('return array(' . $_GET['documents'] . ');');
    foreach ($documents as $document) {
        // Processing document ...
    }
}

In this example, an attacker sends a malware code to a script, and the application executes this code. The figure shows an attack example via phpinfo function:

Figure 1. Arbitrary Code Execution attack

Recommendations

To eliminate the vulnerability, conduct application refactoring to ensure it does not include sections that dynamically generate executable code. We also recommend executing application code in isolated environment.

Links

  • Code Injection https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Code_Injection
  • CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection') http://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html
